<h3>Setup</h3>
<div class="table">
    <div class="table-row">
        <div class="table-cell tc-6">
            <!-- Board Setup -->
            <h4>Board Setup</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>2 voters per state from party that wins tie breaker</li>
                
                <li>divide remaining cards into 3 piles: 1 for each month</li>
                <li>2 debate topic cards</li>
                <li>2 debate city tiles</li>
                <li><u>Breaking News:</u>
                    <ul>
                        <li>draw 9 cards, others to box</li>
                        <li>3 into August deck after dealing start hands</li>
                        <li>3 into other decks after post-debate redraws</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="table-cell tc-6">
            <!-- Player Setup -->
            <h4>Player Setup</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>5 cards</li>
                <li>2 candidate cards: keep 1, return 1</li>
                <li>X voters to supply of registered voters (double when no VP)</li>
                <li>$X (double when no VP)</li>
                <li>Choose a home state
                    <ul>
                        <li>from among the <i>reference states</i> shown on cards they have</li>
                        <li>add 2 voters from the undecided supply</li>
                        <li>no restrictions on home state, every P & VP can choose the same</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><u>Election Day:</u>
                    <ul>
                        <li>3 exit poll cards to each <i>party</i></li>
                        <li>3 state return cards to each <i>party</i></li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<hr />

<h3>Teams</h3>
<ul>
    <li>parties share registered voters and money</li>
    <li>turn order goes party by party</li>
    <li>within a party's turn, players choose which goes first each round</li>
    <li>team may exchange cards after finishing both turns
        <ul>
            <li>must be in same <i>region</i></li>
            <li>must be X:X trade, max 3:3</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h3>2-party game:</h3>
<ul>
    <li>do not place voters for the party not in play</li>
    <li>place <i>one</i> voter of the party matching the secondary (or third) tie-breaker</li>
    <li>2-player game: before shuffling action cards, remove cards with X[2-player] symbol</li>
    <li>5-player game:
        <ul>
            <li>5th player plays both roles for the party</li>
            <li>1 candidate pawn, 1 hand of cards, 1 home state marker</li>
            <li>double money, double registered voters</li>
            <li>takes 2 full turns in a row</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ul>

    
    

@*    ***
    these rules were written under the assumption of base game (3 parties) but only using 2-parties
    ergo, we can extend this to the general situation of using the playmat (4 parties) but using less than 4 parties
    1. do not place counters in the groove of any party not in play. instead, place counters of states with a primary tiebreaker of an unused party in the groove of the in-play party matching the highest tiebreaker.
    2. do not place any voters for a party that is not in play. instead, in states with a first tiebreaker of an unused party, place _one_ voter of the party matching the second tiebreaker ... unless the second tiebreaker party is also not in play. in that case, place _one_ voter of the party matching the third tiebreaker

    assume a state uses tiebreaker ordering RBG

